<section xml:id="C24.S10">
<title>Arithmetic Properties</title>        
   
<subsection xml:id="C24.S10.SS1">
<title>Von Staudt–Clausen Theorem</title>          
<para xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.s1">
Here and elsewhere in §24.10 the symbol <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m1">p</Math> denotes a prime number.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.s2">
<Math equation-number="24.10.1" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E1">B_{2n}+\sum_{(p-1)\mathbin{|}2n}\frac{1}{p}=\hbox{integer},</Math> where the summation is over all <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m2">p</Math> such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m3">p-1</Math> divides <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m4">2n</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.s3">
The denominator of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m5">B_{2n}</Math> is the product of all these primes <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m6">p</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.s4">
<Math equation-number="24.10.2" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E2">pB_{2n}\equiv p-1\pmod{p^{\ell+1}},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m7">n\geq 2</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m8">\ell(\geq 1)</Math> is an arbitrary integer such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.m9">(p-1)p^{\ell}\mathbin{|}2n</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="5" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C24.S10.SS1.p1.s5">
Here and elsewhere two rational numbers arecongruent if the modulus divides the numerator of their difference.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S10.SS2">
<title>Kummer Congruences</title>            
<para xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="24.10.3" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E3">\frac{B_{m}}{m}\equiv\frac{B_{n}}{n}\pmod{p},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m1">m\equiv n\not\equiv 0\pmod{p-1}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.s2">
<Math equation-number="24.10.4" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E4">(1-p^{m-1})\frac{B_{m}}{m}\equiv(1-p^{n-1})\frac{B_{n}}{n}\pmod{p^{\ell+1}},</Math> valid when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m2">m\equiv n\pmod{(p-1)p^{\ell}}</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m3">n\not\equiv 0\pmod{p-1}</Math> , where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m4">\ell(\geq 0)</Math> is a fixed integer.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.s3">
<Math equation-number="24.10.5" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E5">E_{n}\equiv E_{n+p-1}\pmod{p},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m5">p(&gt;2)</Math> is a prime and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m6">n\geq 2</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.s4">
<Math equation-number="24.10.6" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E6">E_{2n}\equiv E_{2n+w}\pmod{2^{\ell}},</Math> valid for fixed integers <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m7">\ell(\geq 0)</Math> , and for all <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m8">n(\geq 0)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m9">w(\geq 0)</Math> such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS2.p1.m10">2^{\ell}\mathbin{|}w</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S10.SS3">
<title>Voronoi’s Congruence</title>          
<para xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.s1">
Let <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m1">B_{2n}=\ifrac{N_{2n}}{D_{2n}}</Math> , with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m2">N_{2n}</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m3">D_{2n}</Math> relatively prime and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m4">D_{2n}&gt;0</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.s2">
Then <Math equation-number="24.10.7" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E7">(b^{2n}-1)N_{2n}\equiv{2nb^{2n-1}D_{2n}\sum_{k=1}^{M-1}k^{2n-1}\left\lfloor \frac{kb}{M}\right\rfloor\pmod{M}},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m5">M(\geq 2)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m6">b</Math> are integers, with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m7">b</Math> relatively prime to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p1.m8">M</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
<para xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C24.S10.SS3.p2.s1">
For historical notes, generalizations, and applications, seePorubský (1998).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S10.SS4">
<title>Factors</title>           
<para xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.s1">
With <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m1">N_{2n}</Math> as in §24.10(iii)
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.s2">
<Math equation-number="24.10.8" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E8">N_{2n}\equiv 0\pmod{p^{\ell}},</Math> valid for fixed integers <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m2">\ell(\geq 1)</Math> , and for all <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m3">n(\geq 1)</Math> such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m4">2n\not\equiv 0</Math> <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m5">\pmod{p-1}</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m6">p^{\ell}\mathbin{|}2n</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="15" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.s3">
<Math equation-number="24.10.9" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S10.E9">E_{2n}\equiv\begin{cases}0\pmod{p^{\ell}}&amp;\text{if }p\equiv 1\pmod{4},\\ 2\pmod{p^{\ell}}&amp;\text{if }p\equiv 3\pmod{4},\end{cases}</Math> valid for fixed integers <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m7">\ell(\geq 1)</Math> and for all <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m8">n(\geq 1)</Math> such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S10.SS4.p1.m9">(p-1)p^{\ell-1}\mathbin{|}2n</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
</section>
